===Noun===
{{examples|sense=grammar|* ''Bread, butter '''and''' cheese.''}}
{{en-noun|~}}

# The [[act]] of [[join]]ing, or [[condition]] of being joined.
#: {{synonyms|en|connection|union}}
#* {{RQ:Eliot Middlemarch|book=I|chapter=XVIII|passage={{...|If Mr. Bulstrode insisted, as he was apt to do, on the Lutheran doctrine of justification, as that by which a Church must stand or fall,}} Dr. Minchin in return was quite sure that man was not a mere machine or a fortuitous '''conjunction''' of atoms; {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1896|title=Familiar Studies of Men and Books|author=Robert Louis Stevenson|authorlink=Robert Louis Stevenson|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/425/425-h/425-h.htm|passage=About them all there is that sort of stiff quaint unreality, that '''conjunction''' of the grotesque, and even of a certain bourgeois snugness, with passionate contortion and horror, that is so characteristic of Gothic art.}}
# {{lb|en|grammar}} A word used to join other words or phrases together into sentences. The specific conjunction used shows how the two joined parts are related.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1881|title=The Verbalist|author=Alfred Ayres [pseudonym; Thomas Embly Osmun]|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/22457/22457-h/22457-h.htm|passage=A comma is placed between short members of compound sentences, connected by ''and'', ''but'', ''for'', ''nor'', ''or'', ''because'', ''whereas'', ''that'' expressing purpose (so that, in order that), and other '''conjunctions'''.}}
# [[cooccurrence|Cooccurrence]]; [[coincidence]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1843|title={{w|A System of Logic}}|volume=1|author=John Stuart Mill|authorlink=John Stuart Mill|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/26495/26495-h/26495-h.html|passage={{...|But where it is seen what the phenomenon is, there is seldom any difficulty in seeing that the assertion conveyed by the proposition is,}} the coexistence of one such phenomenon with another; or the succession of one such phenomenon to another: their '''''conjunction''''', in short, so that where the one is found, we may calculate on finding both.}}
# {{lb|en|astronomy}} The alignment of two bodies in the [[solar system]] such that they have the same [[longitude]] when seen from Earth.
#: {{hyponyms|en|grand conjunction|great conjunction|inferior conjunction|superior conjunction|topocentric conjunction}}
#: {{antonyms|en|opposition}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011|title=Starf*cker{{...|: The Catastrophic Conjunction of Venus and Mars}}|publisher=Ev Cochrane|isbn=9780977285129|page=140|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=PyftdgOHwtAC&lpg=PA60&dq=%22conjunction%22%20stars&hl=&pg=PA140#v=onepage&q=%22conjunction%22&f=false||text=The spectacular '''conjunction''' of Venus and Mars gave rise to a myriad of mythical interpretations.}}
# {{lb|en|astrology}} An [[aspect]] in which planets are in close proximity to one another.
# {{lb|en|logic}} The [[proposition]] resulting from the combination of two or more propositions using the [[∧]] (<math>\and</math>) [[operator]].
#: {{cot|en|disjunction}}
#: {{meronyms|en|conjunct|logical connective}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[sexual intercourse|Sexual intercourse]].
